div.font: Adds positional information to each token embedding.
div.span: transformer architecture is that it is order invariant:

lthough the token embeddings are stored within a tensor in their input order, this ordering is not exposed to any of the computations within the model. But word order matters for language, and nearby tokens are usually much more relevant to predicting the next word than a random token from three pages prior.

div.style: text-align: left;
div.span: There are many approaches to adding position information (absolute or relative) to the token embeddings or attention calculation. GPT-2 simply parameterizes it, and allows the model itself to figure out how to represent token position.
This means that the size of this matrix must be defined at training time, thereby fixing the maximum sequence length (context length) that the model can process.

div.div:
Residual stream
= 3 768
(-dimensional latent space)
Carries the embeddings and outputs from all prior layer to each subsequent layer of the model.The residual stream is thecentral communication channel in a transformer; it doesn't do any processing itself and all layers communicate through it.Each attention and MLP sublayerreads in the residual stream, performs some computation, and then adds the result back to the residual stream.
Importantly, this is the only way in which the residual stream is acted on. It is otherwise a straight shot between the Embed and Unembed layers. There aren't any non-linearities ormultiplicative interactions such as scaling, shearing, or rotation. The embeddings are only modified via summation with sublayer outputs.
This linear, additive structure has several important consequences. First, the residual stream is effectively aseries of end-to-end skip connections.Since addition preserves the full gradient during back propagation, the gradient can flow with full magnitude backwards through the residual stream to every layerduring training, making it feasible to train very deep models.
Second, because the residual stream is linear (more than merely linear...), information written by one layer can pass through multiple layers without being destroyed.All components of a transformer (token embedding, attention heads, MLP layers, and Unembed) communicate with each other by reading from and writing to different subspaces of the residual stream. ... This means that layers can send different information to different layers by storing it in different subspaces. ...Once added, information persists in a subspace unless another layer ... deletes it.
This persistence offers significant flexibility in how information flows through the model:
This means that the computations that transformers perform needn't run through every layer: computational circuits can optimize their pathing, going, e.g., from an attention head in layer 2, through an MLP in layer 5, to an attention head in layer 8, and so on. [cite NN]Each such circuit is free to use its own encoding.All of theseencoded messages from one layer to another to another arelayered on top of another in the residual stream. This makesthe residual stream itself not a particularly tractable target for interpretability work. [instead: decompose the computational paths]
The residual stream can be seen as the model's shared, working memory. It is the only way that information can move between layers, and so the model needs to find a way to store all relevant information in there (NN)
Ergo, under high demand, and expect it to exhibit significant superposition.

div.div: Decoder transformers implement causal attention: each embedding can only attend to itself and prior embeddings. In practice this is often implemented by a masking step after taking the dot product of all pairs of embeddings. It is displayed here conceptually, with each embedding only interacting with itself and its preceding embeddings.

div.div: Transforms each input vector independently to have mean 0 and variance 1, then scales and shifts each component of the normalized vector bya learned scaling factor () and shifting factor (). (Each LayerNorm layer has a -length and which is applied component-wise.)

Purpose:The initial normalization promotes consistent distributions of input to a layer by reducing covariate shift (Ba et al., 2016),therebystabilizing gradients and speeding up training. The parameterized scale and shift then return some flexibility to the model, allowing it to optimize the transformation for each layer.

Implications:In the GPT-2 architecture, LayerNormmediates every read of the residual stream (en routeto each attention or MLP sublayer, and before Unembed). Because LayerNorm is anon-linear transformation,it complicates interpretability, which prominent researchershave expressed frustration about.

In principle, the non-linearity in LayerNorm can perform useful computation, and it can even work as a general-purpose activation function. In practice, within LLM architectures, it is an open question whether LayerNorm performs any meaningful computation or if it is merely an artifact of the training process.Attempts have been made to train more interpretable models without LayerNorm, and a recent preprintclaims to have removed GPT-2's LayerNorm layers with fine-tuning with only minor performance degradation, suggesting it does not play a crucial roleat inference time.

Q/K/V matrices

Each attention head has its own Query, Key, and Value matrix. Each vector from the residual stream is (after LayerNorm) multiplied by each of these matrices, to form three lower-dimensional projections.
